👉 Is multiple inheritance allowed in JAVA ?

Multiple Inheritance face problems when there exist methods with same signature in both the super classes.
Due to such problems , JAVA does not support multiple inheritance directly but the similar concept can be achieved using interfaces.
A class can implement multiple interfaces and extend a class at the same time.

Note : 

1. Interfaces in JAVA is a bit like the class but with a significant difference.
2. An interface can only have method signatures, fields and defualt methods.
3. The class implementing an interface needs to on declare the methods ( not fields ).
4. You can create a reference of Interfaces but not the object.
5. Interfaces methods are public by default.

👉 Default Methods : 

An interface can have static and default methods 
Default methods enables us to add new functionality to existing Interfaces.
This feature was introduced in JAVA 8 to ensure backward compatibility while updating an interface.
classes implementing the interface need not implemented the default methods.
Interfaces can also include private methods for default methods to use.

👉 Inheritance in Interfaces

Interfaces can extend another interfaces : 

public interface Interface1{
  void meth1();
}
public interface Interface2 extends Interface1{
  void meth2();
}

Remember that Interface cannot implement another interface, only classes can do that!

👉 Polymorphism using Interfaces

ⓒ Class  
ⓘ Interface  
   +------------+       +----+        +--------+        +--------------+
ⓒ | Cell Phone |    ⓘ | GPS |     ⓘ | Camera |     ⓘ | Media Player |
   +------------+       +----+        +--------+        +--------------+
        |                  |               |                    |
        +------------------+---------------+--------------------+
                                  ↓
                           +---------------+
                           | Smart Phone   |
                           +---------------+

Similar to Dynamic method Dispatch in Inheritance 
                                                  ⤵️
                                                  GPS g = new SmartPhone(); --> Can only use GPS methods
                                           SmartPhone S = new SmartPhone(); --> Can only use SmartPhone methods

Implementing an Interface forces methods implementation.


Example Code :

// Interface 1
interface GPS {
    void getLocation();

    // Default method
    default void showMap() {
        System.out.println("Showing map using GPS...");
    }
}

//  Interface 2
interface Camera {
    void takePhoto();

    default void recordVideo() {
        System.out.println("Recording video...");
    }
}

//  Interface 3
interface MediaPlayer {
    void playMusic();

    default void stopMusic() {
        System.out.println("Stopping music...");
    }
}

//  Base Class
class CellPhone {
    void call() {
        System.out.println("Calling...");
    }

    void pickCall() {
        System.out.println("Picking call...");
    }
}

//  Child Class (Multiple Inheritance using Interfaces)
class SmartPhone extends CellPhone implements GPS, Camera, MediaPlayer {

    // Implementing all interface methods
    public void getLocation() {
        System.out.println("Getting current location...");
    }

    public void takePhoto() {
        System.out.println("Taking photo...");
    }

    public void playMusic() {
        System.out.println("Playing music...");
    }

    // Own method
    void browseInternet() {
        System.out.println("Browsing internet...");
    }
}

// Main Class
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // Polymorphism using Interface
        GPS g = new SmartPhone();
        g.getLocation();     // Allowed
        g.showMap();         // Default method

        // g.takePhoto();  Not allowed (reference type is GPS)

        System.out.println();

        // Full access using class reference
        SmartPhone s = new SmartPhone();
        s.call();            // From CellPhone
        s.getLocation();     // From GPS
        s.takePhoto();       // From Camera
        s.playMusic();       // From MediaPlayer
        s.browseInternet();  // Own method

        System.out.println();

        // Another interface reference
        Camera c = new SmartPhone();
        c.takePhoto();
        c.recordVideo();
    }
}
